{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}} {{BLP sources|date=July 2011}} '''Gracy''' is a [[Malayalam literature|Malayalam]] author.<ref>{{cite book |title=Handbook of twentieth-century literatures of India |last=Natarajan |first=Nalini |author2=Emmanuel Sampath Nelson |pages=198–199 |year=1996 |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]] |isbn=978-0-313-28778-7 }}</ref> Her first collection of [[Short story|short stories]], ''Padiyirangippoya Parvati'', was published in 1991.<ref>{{cite book |title=Growing up as a woman writer |last=Jain |first=Jasbir |page=352 |year=2007 |publisher=[[Sahitya Akademi]] |isbn=978-81-260-2547-3 }}</ref> Her awards include the [[Malayalam Literary Awards#Lalithambika Sahitya Award|Lalithambika Antharjanam Award]] (1995), the Thoppil Ravi Award (1997), the Katha Prize for the Best Malayalam Short Story (1998) and the [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]] (2000).<ref>{{cite book |title=Katha prize stories, Volume 8 |last=Dharmarajan |first=Geeta |page=305 |year=1998 |publisher=[[Katha Books]] |isbn=978-81-85586-85-4 }}</ref> Her major works are Narakavaathil, Randu Swapna Darsikal, Kaveriyude Neru, Eezbu Penkathakal, Panikkannu and a collection, Gracyude Kathakal. Her stories have been translated into [[English language|English]], [[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Tamil language|Tamil]] and [[Oriya language|Oriya]]. She was the head of the Malayalam department, Al-Ameen college, Edathala, Aluva.
==Awards== # 1995: [[Malayalam Literary Awards#Lalithambika Sahitya Award|Lalithambika Antharjanam Award]] (1995) # 1997: Thoppil Ravi Award - ''Bhrantan Pookkal'' # 1998: Katha Prize for the Best Malayalam Short Story - "Paanchaali" # 2000: [[Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award]] (Collection of short stories) - ''Randu Swapna Darshikal''
